premise_source_doc_sentence: Desmethylcitalopram is an active metabolite of the antidepressant drugs citalopram  (  racemic  )  and escitalopram  (  the S-enantiomer , which would be called desmethylescitalopram  )  .
An established INN is known as a recommended INN  (  rINN  )  , while a name that is still being considered is called a proposed INN  (  pINN  )  .

Like citalopram and escitalopram , didesmethyl  (  es  )  citalopram functions as a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor  (  SSRI  )  , and is responsible for some of its parents ' therapeutic benefits .

It is based on the observation that the R isomer of citalopram can decrease the potency and inhibit the effects of the S isomer , probably through an allosteric interaction between two distinct , non-overlapping binding sites for the two different isomers on the serotonin transporter .
Whether escitalopram exhibits superior therapeutic properties to citalopram or merely represents an example of `` evergreening '' is controversial .
